2016 Presidential Campaign Contributor Data in California

Andrew Yip

11/4/2015

The questions

This project explores the 2016 Presidential Campaign Contributor Data in California. It aims to understand the characteristics of the contributors in CA and their relationship with the candidates, their political parties, and their finances in general.

Specifically: 1. How do top-financed candidates in each party position themselves among donors? 2. How do the parties differ in the temporal and spatial dimensions of fund-raising? 3. What are the characteristics of donors in correspondance to their financial contribution to a candidate?

Data cleaning

The data is retrieved from the Federal Election Commission, where the File Format is also available, describing all the fields.

First, load the libraries and read the data, and also read the candidate summary retrieved from the FEC. The metadata is also available.

The data is then corrected for data type; mundane cloumns are removed. cmte_id, cand_id, and cand_nm are redundant, so only the cand_id is kept. We retain the correspondence of these relations in the candidateSummary DF. The date column contb_receipt_dt is converted to POSIXct class for time manipulation. receipt_desc, memo_cd, memo_text, form_tp, tran_id, and election_tp are redacted as they only contain mundane information, the omission of which would not affect the analysis. contbr_st is CA for all observations so can also be eliminated. The 18 columns reduce to 9.

ca$contb_receipt_dt <- dmy(ca$contb_receipt_dt)
ca <- ca %>% select(cand_id, contbr_nm:contbr_city, contbr_zip:contb_receipt_dt, 
    file_num) %>% data.frame

Financing characteristics

First, we need to clean the data for duplicate categories such as SELF-EMPLOYED, SELF EMPLOYED, SELF, NONE, NOT EMPLOYED, etc in the employer column. For this study, we will group them using the occupation column under NOT EMPLOYED and SELF EMPLOYED. Before doing so, lets side-track and investigate whether theres a self-perceived difference within the NOT EMPLOYED and SELF EMPLOYED groups in reported employer and their compaign contribution amount.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot 1: Candidate Positioning in Fund-raising

In relation to the first question, lets look at the relations of the size of total contribution, the weight of unitemized contributions (under $200), and the party affiliation.

cand %>% mutate(ind_ite_fra = signif(ind_ite_con/tot_con, 3), ind_uni_fra = signif(ind_uni_con/tot_con, 
    3)) %>% select(can_nam, can_par_aff, ind_ite_fra, ind_uni_fra, tot_con) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(x = tot_con, y = ind_uni_fra, color = can_par_aff, label = sapply(strsplit(can_nam, 
        split = ",", fixed = T), function(x) x[1]))) + geom_text() + theme_bw() + 
    labs(x = "Total Contribution (USD)", y = "Fraction of contribution under $200", 
        color = "Party", title = "Positioning of candidates in fund-raising")

Out of the four democratic candidates who received contributions from CA, Clinton and Sanders lead in total contributions, with very different constituents of the funding source. 80% of Sanders individual contributions are small contributions under $200 each, where Clinton stands at 20%. Also note that Clinton receives double the amount of contributions to that of Sanders. Among Republican candidates, Carson receives most contribution in aggregate, while the top three Republican candidates in terms of total contributions do not see such a big variance as among the Democrats. It is also interesting to note that the top three Republican candidates span the space among the different proportions of small contributions, with Carson catering to the small donars, and Bush to the large, and Cruz holding a middle position. Personally, it is surprising to see Trump has a rather low percentage in contributions greater than $200, while his total contribution is not as high, contrary to his media image. It also seems that the Hotellings law does not hold in terms of political positioning on total contributions within ones political party, where differentiation in the size of individual contributions pays off.

Plot 2: Temporal aggregation in contribution

In relation to the second question we explore the temporal behavior in campaign contribution for the 9 largest occupations for each party respectively from May 2015.

ca %>% mutate(t = ymd(contb_receipt_dt), party = parties[cand_id]) %>% filter(contbr_occupation %in% 
    occupation$contbr_occupation[1:9], party %in% c("DEM", "REP"), t > "2015-05-01") %>% 
    group_by(party, contbr_occupation, t) %>% summarize(sum = sum(contb_receipt_amt)) %>% 
    mutate(cumsum = with_order(t, cumsum, sum)) %>% ggplot(aes(x = t, y = cumsum, 
    color = contbr_occupation)) + geom_line() + facet_grid(party ~ .) + scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set3") + 
    theme_bw() + labs(x = "Time", y = "USD", color = "Occupation", title = "Commulative contribution by occupation")

Here we observe an obvious kink in the republican total contribution at the end of June, and a steady increase in total contribution from the two most important sectors, retired and homemakers. On the contrast, demoncratic total contribution sees a more linear trend from the top performing sectors, the attorneys and the retired. The not employed is a particular strong hold with the Democrats, with an increasing trend over time.

Plot 3: A simple model on party affiliation and contribution amount

To investigate the third question of how the characteristics of the donor relate to their support of a particular party. We opt to build a linear model to predict party affiliation based on the donors contribution amount and other traits. Since the dimensions of the factor variables are large, we opt to only take the top 15 occupations combined across parties as a predictor.

partyint <- c(0, 1)
names(partyint) <- c("DEM", "REP")
modeldata <- ca %>% mutate(par_aff = partyint[parties[cand_id]]) %>% filter(par_aff %in% 
    c(0, 1), contbr_occupation %in% occupation$contbr_occupation[1:15]) %>% 
    select(contb_receipt_amt, par_aff, contbr_occupation)
model <- lm(par_aff ~ contb_receipt_amt + contbr_occupation, modeldata)

The model illustrates significance in predicting party support based on donors occupation and contribution, where the occupations have most weight in terms of predicting ones affiliation. The signs of effect of the professions agree with the prior explorations.

Reflection

The categorical columns have been messy and difficult to clean due to the inherent duplicative nature of self-reported fields. In particular, the self-employed and not-employed categories overlap without clear delineation. The lack of finer spatial grouping of the donors other than zipcode has made a spatial investigation of the data difficult. This data-analysis exerperience has been both challenging and rewarding. I look forward to more predictive analyses on election data with more scalar variables, which could include household income, family size, home size, etc, for a better characterization of the donors behavior with their traits.
